<div id="review_523386571" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/523386571" />
    <a title="Janet Gardner" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4445120-janet-gardner"><img alt="Janet Gardner" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1359731175p2/4445120.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/523386571?book_show_action=true">Feb 01, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Janet Gardner" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Janet Gardner" href="/user/show/4445120-janet-gardner">Janet Gardner</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781625584694" href="/book/show/17248306-the-narrative-of-sojourner-truth">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4445120-janet-gardner?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4445120-janet-gardner?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer523386571" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4489913663718534441">Sojourner Truth is one of those people I’ve known about for decades, but the only thing of hers I’d actually read was the famous “Ain’t I a Woman?” speech (which, of course, was written and re-written over the years and may not be a very clear representation of the extemporaneous oration she gave). On the whole, I found this oral history quite interesting, and of course very sad and moving. For my own purposes, though, I wish it had spent more time on her days in slavery and immediately after, a</span>
  <span id="freeText4489913663718534441" style="display:none">Sojourner Truth is one of those people I’ve known about for decades, but the only thing of hers I’d actually read was the famous “Ain’t I a Woman?” speech (which, of course, was written and re-written over the years and may not be a very clear representation of the extemporaneous oration she gave). On the whole, I found this oral history quite interesting, and of course very sad and moving. For my own purposes, though, I wish it had spent more time on her days in slavery and immediately after, and a bit less detailing the specifics of her theology, her differences with the Matthias Delusion and Second Advent Doctrines and the like. From this remove of history (or, at least from my own perspective) that stuff is far less interesting than how a tough, illiterate slave made a name and place for herself in an unwelcoming world.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4489913663718534441" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


