      <div id="aboutAuthor" class=" clearFloats bigBox"><div class="h2Container gradientHeaderContainer"><h2 class="brownBackground"><a href="/author/show/200277.Sojourner_Truth">About Sojourner Truth</a></h2></div><div class="bigBoxBody"><div class="bigBoxContent containerWithHeaderContent">
          <div class='bookAuthorProfile'>
<div class='bookAuthorProfile__topContainer'>
<div class='bookAuthorProfile__photoContainer'>
<a href="/author/show/200277.Sojourner_Truth"><div class='bookAuthorProfile__photo' style='background-image: url(https://images.gr-assets.com/authors/1211293345p3/200277.jpg);'></div>
</a></div>
<div class='bookAuthorProfile__widgetContainer'>
<div class='bookAuthorProfile__name'>
<a href="/author/show/200277.Sojourner_Truth">Sojourner Truth
</a></div>
<div class='bookAuthorProfile__followerCount'>
95
followers
</div>

</div>
</div>
<div class='bookAuthorProfile__about'>

<span id="freeTextContainer7482532934053195818">Sojourner Truth (1797–November 26, 1883) was the self-given name, from 1843, of Isabella Baumfree, an American abolitionist and women&apos;s rights activist. Truth was born into slavery in Swartekill, New York. Her best-known speech, &quot;Ain&apos;t I a Woman?,&quot; was delivered in 1851 at the Ohio Women&apos;s Rights Convention in Akron, Ohio.</span>
  <span id="freeText7482532934053195818" style="display:none">Sojourner Truth (1797–November 26, 1883) was the self-given name, from 1843, of Isabella Baumfree, an American abolitionist and women's rights activist. Truth was born into slavery in Swartekill, New York. Her best-known speech, "Ain't I a Woman?," was delivered in 1851 at the Ohio Women's Rights Convention in Akron, Ohio.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7482532934053195818" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

</div>
</div>

